Show HN: See” a Terminal File Opener
text:
Hi HN,

This is a tool I wrote to associate file extensions with the command to render those files in the terminal.

Think of "see" as terminal equivalent of double clicking an file in the desktop. You keep a mapping of extension on to commands.

This may feel like a solved problem, but a straw poll on Twitter indicated that there was nothing that worked quite like this. This solution feels like how I would expect things to work. There are comparisons with existing alternatives (that I know of) in the README.

I don't know what direction this tool will go. If there is interest, I might develop it a little further (although it feels like something that should have a super-minimal set of features). It was under a day's work, so I wouldn't feel too bad if ends up being a tool that only I use.

title: Ask HN: Best hardware investment for learning ML in 2023?
text:
Hi HN'ers, I'm a new grad / software engineer and have decided to learn ML and experiment with some models. I wanted to buy a PC for coding and ML experiments. I want to try running larger models and perhaps experiment with new architectures too. I am also very interested in RL. (I am aware that I cannot compete with companies like OpenAI in terms of compute power but I still have a hope of doing something new in terms of application or architecture).

What would you consider the best investment for a begginer? Would a M2 Mac be a good choice? My main concern is that my initial investment should be extensible, so I could add more compute/GPUs later if required.
